{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492393"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1046"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1046"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.01,0.03,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97984"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"439"},{"type":"tags","id":"8850"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49617"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents with an itchy, painful nodular swelling adjacent in his left eyelid (see image). This has been present for the past two days.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular warm compresses","Intra-lesional steroid","Topical tetracycline","Oral doxycycline","Incision and curettage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a chalazion and has formed as the result of obstruction of a sebaceous gland. They are usually painless swellings. In this case the chalazion has become infected, the most commonly agent being Staphylococcus Aureus. The history of pain and the erythematous nodule indicate an acute infection. Initial management approach is with conservative measures, including lid hygiene and soft, \u003Cstrong\u003Eregular warm compresses\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach will produce resolution in about 50% of cases by helping to facilitate drainage of the abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E has anti-inflammatory and antibacterial actions and is second line to warm compresses. It can be used in repeated chalazia to alter Meibomian gland secretion. A topical antibiotic such as \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical tetracycline\u003C/strong\u003E can be used if there is associated blepharitis. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and curettage\u003C/strong\u003E may be required if the medical measures do not work after 3-4 weeks. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntra-lesional steroid\u003C/strong\u003E injection can cause permanent skin depigmentation or atrophy and is not recommended in the periocular region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chalazion will present with a nodular swelling under the eyelid. Secondary infection can be present.","Initial management of a chalazion is with lid hygiene and regular warm compresses."],"references":["Lindsley K, Nichols JJ, Dickersin K. Interventions for acute internal hordeolum. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2010;(9):CD007742. Published 2010 Sep 8. doi:10.1002/14651858.CD007742.pub2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97984"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1046"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18604"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id"